Introduction ¶

This dataset was downloaded from UCI Machine Learning Repository. The two datasets are related to red and white variants of the Portuguese "Vinho Verde" wine. For more details, consult: [Web Link] or the reference [Cortez et al., 2009]. Due to privacy and logistic issues, only physicochemical (inputs) and sensory (the output) variables are available (e.g. there is no data about grape types, wine brand, wine selling price, etc.).

These datasets can be viewed as classification or regression tasks. The classes are ordered and not balanced (e.g. there are many more normal wines than excellent or poor ones). Outlier detection algorithms could be used to detect the few excellent or poor wines.

In this project, the quality score is categorized into two bins of low quality and high quality wine. It aims to use different classifier models, compare and choose the best model to predict the quality of wine i.e. Low or High quality.

from scipy import stats

#Function to detect outliers above or below 3 sigma value in the normal distribution
def drop_numerical_outliers(df, z_thresh=3):
    # outliers will contain `True` or `False` depending on if it is a value below the threshold.
    outliers = df.select_dtypes(include=[np.number]) \
        .apply(lambda x: np.abs(stats.zscore(x)) < z_thresh) \
        .all(axis=1)
    # Drop (inplace) values set to be rejected
    df.drop(df.index[~outliers], inplace=True)
    return df

# Shuffle the Dataset.
shuffled_df = wine_bins.sample(frac=1,random_state=4)

# Put all the low quality wine in a separate dataset.
lq_df = shuffled_df.loc[shuffled_df['quality_range'] == 0]

#Randomly select 2142 observations from the high quality wine (majority class)
hq_df = shuffled_df.loc[shuffled_df['quality_range'] == 1].sample(n=2142,random_state=21)

# Concatenate both dataframes again
normalized_df = pd.concat([hq_df, lq_df])

#plot the dataset after the undersampling
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))

Quick Guide on Classification Metrics¶

Classification models' performances are measured by Precision, Recall, F1-score and AUC-ROC curves. They are as follows -

Curves¶

ROC is a probability curve and AUC represents degree or measure of separability. It tells how much model is capable of distinguishing between classes

Classification Models ¶

Function to obtain Confusion matrix & metrics ¶

In [27]:
def make_confusion_matrix(cf,
                          group_names=None,
                          categories='auto',
                          count=True,
                          percent=True,
                          cbar=True,
                          xyticks=True,
                          xyplotlabels=True,
                          sum_stats=True,
                          stats_list = True,
                          figsize=None,
                          cmap='Blues',
                          title=None):
    '''
    This function will make a pretty plot of an sklearn Confusion Matrix cm using a Seaborn heatmap visualization.
    Arguments
    ---------
    cf:            confusion matrix to be passed in
    group_names:   List of strings that represent the labels row by row to be shown in each square.
    categories:    List of strings containing the categories to be displayed on the x,y axis. Default is 'auto'
    count:         If True, show the raw number in the confusion matrix. Default is True.
    normalize:     If True, show the proportions for each category. Default is True.
    cbar:          If True, show the color bar. The cbar values are based off the values in the confusion matrix.
                   Default is True.
    xyticks:       If True, show x and y ticks. Default is True.
    xyplotlabels:  If True, show 'True Label' and 'Predicted Label' on the figure. Default is True.
    sum_stats:     If True, display summary statistics below the figure. Default is True.
    figsize:       Tuple representing the figure size. Default will be the matplotlib rcParams value.
    cmap:          Colormap of the values displayed from matplotlib.pyplot.cm. Default is 'Blues'
                   See http://matplotlib.org/examples/color/colormaps_reference.html
                   
    title:         Title for the heatmap. Default is None.
    '''


    # CODE TO GENERATE TEXT INSIDE EACH SQUARE
    blanks = ['' for i in range(cf.size)]

    if group_names and len(group_names)==cf.size:
        group_labels = ["{}\n".format(value) for value in group_names]
    else:
        group_labels = blanks

    if count:
        group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}\n".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()]
    else:
        group_counts = blanks

    if percent:
        group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()/np.sum(cf)]
    else:
        group_percentages = blanks

    box_labels = [f"{v1}{v2}{v3}".strip() for v1, v2, v3 in zip(group_labels,group_counts,group_percentages)]
    box_labels = np.asarray(box_labels).reshape(cf.shape[0],cf.shape[1])


    # CODE TO GENERATE SUMMARY STATISTICS & TEXT FOR SUMMARY STATS
    if sum_stats:
        #Accuracy is sum of diagonal divided by total observations
        accuracy  = np.trace(cf) / float(np.sum(cf))

        #if it is a binary confusion matrix, show some more stats
        if len(cf)==2:
            #Metrics for Binary Confusion Matrices
            precision = cf[1,1] / sum(cf[:,1])
            recall    = cf[1,1] / sum(cf[1,:])
            f1_score  = 2*precision*recall / (precision + recall)
            stats_text = "\n\nAccuracy={:0.3f}\nPrecision={:0.3f}\nRecall={:0.3f}\nF1 Score={:0.3f}".format(
                accuracy,precision,recall,f1_score)
        else:
            stats_text = "\n\nAccuracy={:0.3f}".format(accuracy)
    else:
        stats_text = ""

    # SET FIGURE PARAMETERS ACCORDING TO OTHER ARGUMENTS
    if figsize==None:
        #Get default figure size if not set
        figsize = plt.rcParams.get('figure.figsize')

    if xyticks==False:
        #Do not show categories if xyticks is False
        categories=False


    # MAKE THE HEATMAP VISUALIZATION
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    sns.heatmap(cf,annot=box_labels,fmt="",cmap=cmap,cbar=cbar,xticklabels=categories,yticklabels=categories)

    if xyplotlabels:
        plt.ylabel('True label')
        plt.xlabel('Predicted label' + stats_text)
    else:
        plt.xlabel(stats_text)
    
    if title:
        plt.title(title,fontdict = {'fontsize' : 15})
        
    if stats_list==True:
        #creating a dataframe with classifier and metrics
        make_confusion_matrix.stats_list = pd.DataFrame({'Metrics':['Classifier','Accuracy', 'Precision', 'Recall', 'F1_score'], 'Values':["",accuracy, precision, recall, f1_score]})

Function to predict, score, create Confusion matrix & ROC curve ¶

In [28]:
def classifier_parametrics(classifier,X_test,y_test): 
    '''
    This function will pass a classifier model fit with X_train and y_train data to provide confusion matrix and ROC curve and AUC value.
    Arguments
    ---------
    classifier:    classifer model trained with training data
    X_test:        test data of independent variables
    y_test:        test data of dependent variable
    
    '''   
    # Using the predict function of the classifer to predict the test data values of independent variable(X)
    predictions = classifier.predict(X_test)
    
    #Obtaining the Accuracy score of the model
    score = round(accuracy_score(y_test, predictions), 3)
    
    #Creating a confusion matrix
    cm1 = cm(y_test, predictions)
    
    #Defining the names for the labels in the confusion matrix
    labels = ['True Neg','False Pos','False Neg','True Pos']
    categories = ['Zero', 'One']
    
    #Using the function make_confusion_matrix to obtain the confusion matrix
    make_confusion_matrix(cm1, 
                          group_names=labels,
                          categories=categories, title = "\nConfusion Matrix and Performace Metrics of {} Model".format(re.findall(r'\w+', str(type(classifier)))[-1])
                          )
    #Adding the classifier name to the dataframe
    make_confusion_matrix.stats_list.at[0,'Values'] = re.findall(r'\w+', str(type(classifier)))[-1]
        
    probs = classifier.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]  #Predict probabilities for the test data

    fpr, tpr, thresholds  = roc_curve(y_test, probs) #Get the ROC Curve

    plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
    # Plot ROC curve
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr)
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate = 1 - Specificity Score')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate  = Recall Score')
    plt.title('ROC Curve')
    plt.show()
    print('AUC Degree : ', roc_auc_score(y_test.values, probs))

#Defining variable to store metric parameters of different models
model_parameters = pd.DataFrame({'Metrics':['Classifier','Accuracy', 'Precision', 'Recall', 'F1_score']})

From the above plot, we see that Linear Discriminant Analysis classifier and Gradient boosting Classifier have better accuracy, precision, recall and f1-score than most models. Chossing the best model depends upon the objective. If the business objective is focussed on High Quality, then we use the classifier with high precision. If the objective is focussed on having low number of low quality wines in a given sample then we use the model with high Recall. Among all the classifiers, the one with high precision is the Random Forest Classifier model and one with high recall is Gradient boosting Classifier model. If the objective aims at high precision and recall i.e. correctly classifying both high quality and low quality wines, then Linear Discriminant Analysis model or Gradient boosting Classifier model can be used.
